results.notes:
These puffballs have appeared in the same location (mossy area on lawn) each August/September during the past 10 years; always with the elongated stipe-like sterile base.

Photos follow the same fruit bodies for 13 days.

When I fist started finding these (10 years ago) I tentatively IDed them as Calvatia elata, based upon photos seen in a Bessette field guide. But, many online photos labeled “Calvatia elata” showed fruit bodies that looked much different than these. I decided to finally try to obtain some info other than pictures of immature fruit bodies. Two things now stand out that suggest these do not represent a species of Lycoperdon: 1. mature fruit body does not develop an apical pore. Instead, spore puff out through cracks. 2. Spores feature a short pedicel.

Spores mainly globose 4-4.5; some appearing smooth or nearly so; some appearing to be very finely warty (at 400x); all with short pedicel (1-3 microns).

No other information is available, I hope is enough.

Found under pine, maybe aspen; is too orange to be L. brunneum, to brown to be L. aurantiacum, and have a sterile flap that eliminates L. montanum.

results.notes:

Upon dissecting I noticed a small cut or fold inside the cap body from the center to almost the margin.
